Statutory homelessness

Published 10 October 2017

Last updated 2 March 2018 - see all updates

1. Main facts and figures

  • in 2016/17, there were 59,100 households in 'statutory homelessness' – of those, 35,890 (or 61%) were White households (including White ethnic minorities)

  • 16% of all homeless households were Black, 9% were Asian, 3% were from a Mixed ethnic background and 5% were from the Other ethnic group; ethnicity wasn't known for 6% of homeless households

  • London had the highest overall number of homeless households, and the lowest percentage of homeless households made up of White households (including White ethnic minorities)

  • in 2016/17, there were 3 homeless households for every 1,000 households in England, and 5 for every 1,000 households in London (outside of London it was 2 per 1,000)

  • the London borough with the highest number of homeless households per 1,000 households was Newham (10 per 1,000), where the majority of homeless households were Asian (35%)

Things you need to know

This data only relates to one type of homelessness – 'statutory homelessness' – which requires a household to be unintentionally homeless and demonstrate a priority category need (such as dependent children). It therefore doesn’t include single homeless people without specific vulnerabilities, or those people who don’t approach their local authority for help.

Much of the data at the local authority level is excluded because there are fewer than 5 homeless households in each ethnic group. This information is not available as there is a risk of disclosing personal information.

Homelessness data is collected and reported every 3 months by local authorities in England. More detailed statistics on statutory homelessness by ethnicity across local authorities in England are reported annually. This means less data needs to be excluded in order to avoid disclosing individuals’ identities.

The ethnicity recorded is that of the person within the household making the homelessness application. Ethnicity was unknown for 6% of households.

What the data measures

This data measures the number and percentage of homeless households in England, broken down by ethnic group of the household.

A homeless household is one which the local authority has a duty to house in settled accommodation because its members are unintentionally homeless and in a priority need category, but not sleeping rough. This is sometimes called ‘statutory homelessness’.

Priority need cases are those with dependent children (around two-thirds of cases) or those who have a specific vulnerability such as a disability or experience of domestic violence.

To provide additional context, the downloads include statistics on the rate of homelessness per 1,000 of the population, taken from 2015 population estimates published by the Office for National Statistics.

The ethnic categories used in this data

For this data, ethnicity is broken down into the following broad categories:

  • Asian
  • Black
  • Mixed
  • Other (including Chinese)
  • White
  • Unknown

Data on statutory homelessness was collected for specific ethnic groups from 2006 to 2013. Since then, it has been collected for broad ethnic groups at local authority level to avoid disclosing the identify of individuals. The broad groupings were chosen because they make comparisons easier between data from before and after 2013.

Summary of Statutory homelessness Number of homeless households by ethnicity over time Summary

This data shows that:

  • in 2016/17, there were 59,100 households in 'statutory homelessness' – this is an increase of 1,370 households compared with the previous year, but 14,260 fewer than in 2006/07

  • 35,890 homeless households in 2016/17 were White (including White ethnic minorities), 9,330 were Black, 5,560 were Asian, 1,990 were from a Mixed ethnic background and 2,820 were from the Other ethnic group; ethnicity wasn't known for 3,510 households

  • the White ethnic group saw the largest increase in the number of homeless households between 2015/16 and 2016/17 – an additional 1,690 households

  • the number of homeless households from the Black and Mixed ethnic groups fell by 2% between 2015/16 and 2016/17 (a decrease of 210 Black households and 30 Mixed households)

  • in 2016/7, the number of homeless households from the Asian and Other ethnic groups was at its highest level for 10 years

This data shows that:

  • in 2015/16, the percentage of homeless households that were White was at its lowest level in 10 years at 59% – this is 15 percentage points lower than 2006/07, when 74% of homeless households were White

Download table data for ‘Percentage of homeless households by ethnicity and area’ (CSV) Source data for ‘Percentage of homeless households by ethnicity and area’ (CSV)

Summary of Statutory homelessness Percentage of homeless households by ethnicity and area Summary

This data shows that:

  • in 2016/17, there were 3 homeless households for every 1,000 households in England, and 5 for every 1,000 households in London (outside London there were 2 homeless households per 1,000 households)

  • in London, the 3 boroughs with the highest number of homeless households per 1,000 households were Newham (10 per 1,000), Enfield (8 per 1,000) and Waltham Forest (8 per 1,000)

  • in Newham, the majority of homeless households were Asian (35%), in Enfield the majority were Black (45%), and in Waltham Forest the majority were either White or Black (34% each)

  • outside of London, the 3 local authorities with the highest number of homeless households per 1,000 households were Peterborough in the East of England (8 per 1,000), Birmingham in the West Midlands (8 per 1,000) and Milton Keynes in the South East (7 per 1,000)

  • in these areas, White households made up the majority of homeless households - 74% in Peterborough, 33% in Birmingham, and 53% in Milton Keynes

5. Methodology

All local authorities submit a quarterly return summarising homelessness acceptances in their area. The return includes ethnicity information as well as the reason the household lost their previous home, the reason for priority need, and any use of temporary accommodation.

Suppression rules and disclosure control

Any values based on fewer than 5 responses have been suppressed to avoid disclosing personal information.

To minimise suppression, data has been shown for full financial years rather than quarters.

Rounding

Figures in the charts and tables are rounded to the nearest whole number. Figures in the downloads are rounded to 1 decimal point.

Purpose of data source

Homelessness statistics monitor trends in statutory homelessness, rough sleeping and homelessness prevention and relief.
